tle Honours |url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/history/sqn_hons_ww2_1.html |publisher=RAF website ([[waybackmachine]]) |accessdate=31 October 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061031195332/http://www.raf.mod.uk/history/sqn_hons_ww2_1.html |archivedate=31 October 2006}}\n* {{cite book |ref={{harvid|Simon|1992}}\n|last1=Simon |first1=Heinrich |year=1992 |title=Zeugnisse j\u00fcdischer Kultur. Erinnerungsst\u00e4tten in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, Brandenburg, Berlin, Sachsen-Anhalt, Sachsen und Th\u00fcringen |first2=Klaus |last2=Arlt |first3=Ingrid |last3=Ehlers |first4=Alfred |last4=Etzold |first5=Wolfgang |last5=Madai |publisher=Tourist Verlag |location=Berlin |isbn=978-3-350-00780-6 |display-authors=1}}\n* {{cite book |ref={{harvid|Tooze|2006}}\n|last=Tooze |first=Adam |authorlink=Adam Tooze |title=The Wages of Destruction: The Making and Breaking of the Nazi Economy |year=2006 |publisher=Allen Lane |location=London |isbn=978-0-7139-9566-4|title-link=The Wages of Destruction }}\n* {{cite book |ref={{harvid|Webster|Frankland|1961}}\n|first1=C. K. |last1=Webster |authorlink1=Charles Webster (historian) |first2=Noble |last2=Frankland |authorlink2=Noble Frankland |editor-last=Butler |editor-first=J. R. M. |editorlink=J. R. M. Butler |year=1961 |title=The Strategic Air Offensive Against Germany: 1939\u20131945 |volume=II |series=History of the Second World War, United Kingdom Military Series |publisher=[[HMSO]] |location=London |oclc=163349860}}\n* {{cite book |ref={{harvid|Wilson|2005}}\n|last=Wilson |first=K. |series=Bomber War Trilogy |volume=I |title=Bomber Boys: The RAF Offensive of 1943: The Ruhr, the Dambusters and Bloody Berlin |year=2005 |publisher=Weidenfeld & Nicolson |location=London |isbn=978-0-297-84637-6}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Terry |editor1-first=M. J. |editor2-last=Boyne |editor2-first=W. J. |last=Guilmartin |first=John |year=2006 |series=Military History Symposium series of the United States Air Force Academy |volume=IX |title=Winged Crusade: The Quest for American Air and Space Power |chapter=The Aircraft that Decided World War II: Aeronautical Engineering and Grand Strategy, 1933\u20131945: The American Dimension |publisher=United States Air Force Academy |location=Colorado |chapter-url=https://www.usafa.edu/app/uploads/Harmon44.pdf |chapter-format==pdf |accessdate=7 April 2018 |oclc=1021867870}}\n* {{cite book |last=Murray |first=Williamson |year=1985 |title=Luftwaffe |publisher=Nautical & Aviation |location=USA |isbn=978-0-933852-45-7}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Richards |first1=Denis |last2=St G. Saunders |first2=H. |url=http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/UN/UK/UK-RAF-II/index.html |accessdate=7 April 2018 |series=History of the Second World War, Military Series |title=Royal Air Force 1939\u20131945: The Fight Avails |volume=II |location=London |publisher=[[HMSO]] |year=1975 |orig-year=1954 |edition=pbk. |isbn=978-0-11-771593-6}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Rise and Fall of the German Air Force |id=Air 41/10 |number=248 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2001 |orig-year=1948 |publisher=Air Ministry |location=Richmond, Surrey |edition=repr. Public Record Office War Histories |isbn=978-1-903365-30-4}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://archive.org/details/gov.archives.arc.39156 Video: Allies Pierce Siegfried Line (1945) Part 3, planes of the 8th Air Force are prepared for a raid on Berlin. Crews are briefed, planes take off, and the target is bombed]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/profile_videos?user=wehrwulf1945 Available parts of the film ASCHE-DEUTSCHLAND-1945 to view (on the destruction of Dresden and other German cities)]{{dead link|date=July 2016}}\n* [http://www.calvin.edu/academic/cas/gpa/goeb67.htm The Battle of Berlin [[Joseph Goebbels], speech on ''Die Schlacht um Berlin'' [[Das Reich (newspaper)|Das Reich]], 13 February 1944, pp, 1\u20133]\n\n{{RAF WWII Strategic Bombing}}\n{{WWII city bombing}}\n\n{{coord|52|31|N|13|25|E|source:kolossus-itwiki|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berlin, Battle of}}\n[[Category:Aerial operations and battles of World War II]]\n[[Category:History of the Royal Air Force during World War II]]\n[[Category:World War II strategic bombing of Germany]]\n[[Category:Firebombings]]\n[[Category:Aerial operations and battles of World War II involving the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Aerial operations and battles of World War II involving Germany]]\n[[Category:1940s in Berlin|Battle]]\n[[Category:Military history of Berlin]]\n[[Category:1943 in Germany]]\n[[Category:1944 in Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Eastfarthingan", "label": "safe", "comment": "coord inline", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Berlin_(RAF_campaign)"}
{"title_page": "OpenOCD", "text_new": "{{primary sources|date=July 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox software\n| name = OpenOCD\n| logo = <!-- Image name is enough. -->\n| logo alt = \n| logo caption = \n| screenshot = <!-- Image name is enough. -->\n| screenshot size =\n| screenshot alt = \n| caption = \n| collapsible = <!-- Any text here will collapse the screenshot. -->\n| author = Dominic Rath<ref>{{cite web |title=About OpenOCD |url=http://openocd.org/about/ |website=openocd.org |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n| developer = Paul Fertser, \u00d8yvind Harboe, Spencer Oliver\n| released = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| discontinued = no\n| ver layout = <!-- simple (default) or stacked -->\n| latest release version = 0.10.0\n| latest release date = {{Start date and age|2017|01|22|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite web |title=OpenOCD 0.10.0 release is out |url=http://openocd.org/2017/01/openocd-0-10-0-release-is-out/ |website=Open On-Chip Debugger |accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n| latest preview version = \n| latest preview date = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| repo = https://sourceforge.net/p/openocd/code/\n| programming language = [[C (programming language)|C]]\n| operating system = [[Unix-like]], [[Microsoft Windows]]<ref>{{cite web |title=GNU MCU Eclipse OpenOCD |url=https://github.com/gnu-mcu-eclipse/openocd/releases |website=GitHub.com |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n| platform = \n| size = \n| language = \n| language count = <!-- Number only -->\n| language footnote = \n| genre = \n| license = [[GPL#Version_2|GPLv2]]\n| alexa = \n| website = http://openocd.org\n| standard = \n| AsOf = \n}}\n\n'''OpenOCD''' is a [[free software]] [[In-circuit_emulation#On-chip_debugging|on-chip debugging]], [[in-system programming]] and [[Boundary scan|boundary-scan]] testing tool for various [[ARM architecture|ARM]], [[MIPS architecture|MIPS]] and [[RISC-V]] [[microcontroller|microcontrollers]].<ref>{{cite web |title=OpenOCD User\u2019s Guide |url=http://openocd.org/doc/pdf/openocd.pdf |website=openocd.org |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Why your hardware needs an open source debugger |url=https://opensource.com/life/15/5/open-source-on-chip-debugger |website=opensource.com |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n== What is OpenOCD used for? ==\nWriting firmware code (usually a binary or hex-file) to a microcontroller is called '''\"flashing\"'''. To flash, one needs to perform a series of actions involving several hardware and software tools to be successful. OpenOCD is a very popular software tool that plays an important role in this \"flashing procedure\". Aside from flashing, OpenOCD can also be used to '''\"debug\"''' the firmware. For that purpose engineers typically connect a [[GNU Debugger|GDB client]] to OpenOCD.\n\nA good way to understand OpenOCD's role in flashing and debugging firmware on microcontrollers, is to investigate the \"flashing procedure\" in more detail.\n\n=== The flashing procedure ===\nAbsolutely nothing happens when you switch on a new empty microcontroller, because there is simply no code in its Flash memory. The USB port, serial port, ethernet link - or whatever connectivity your chip supports - won't do anything. However, there is one exception: the JTAG (and/or SWD) link to your microcontroller is always intact. This protocol is burned in the silicon. So even an 'empty' microcontroller receives and processes JTAG (and/or SWD) commands. That's why you typically use JTAG (or SWD) to flash the firmware.\n\nIn theory, you can put a [[bootloader]] in your firmware. This way you only need to flash the firmware once with JTAG (or SWD), and you can flash new firmware using the bootloader. However, it is customary to just use JTAG (or SWD) to flash repeatedly during firmware development.\n\nTo actually send the JTAG (or SWD) commands to a microcontroller, you need a '''\"flash/debug probe\"'''. This probe can be a separate device that you connect to the JTAG (or SWD) pins on the microcontroller through a connector. However, some circuit boards have an on-board flash/debug probe right next to the microcontroller. The connection to the JTAG (or SWD) pins is therefore hard-wired on the circuit board.\n\nThe flash/debug probe usually has a USB connector to connect to your computer. Before using it, you'll need to install the USB driver first, which you should download from the website of the probe manufacturer.\n\nOnce the probe is properly installed on your computer and connected to the correct pins on the microcontrollers, you can start OpenOCD. Assuming you've got OpenOCD installed, you can start it this way from your console:\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\n    $openocd -f openocd_probe.cfg -f openocd_chip.cfg -s <OCDSCRIPTS_LOC> -c \"init; reset halt\"\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nThe files \"openocd_probe.cfg\" and \"openocd_chip.cfg\" are configuration files that describe your probe and microcontroller respectively. You should find these files for your specific microcontroller and probe in the \"scripts\" folder within your OpenOCD installation. Pass these files with the `-f` flag to OpenOCD at startup. Also pass the location to the OpenOCD \"scripts\" folder with the `-s` flag. Finally, you can pass some commands with the `-c` flag that OpenOCD should immediately execute when started.\n\nOpenOCD has no graphical user interface. When it's started, you should see some output in the console telling you if the connection to the microcontroller was successful or not. If successful, OpenOCD starts a \"GDB server\" on TCP port 3333 and a \"Telnet server\" on TCP port 4444 in the background.\n\nOpen a second console and start a Telnet client:\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\n    $telnet 127.0.0.1 4444\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nIn Windows you might need to enable Telnet first:\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\n    > dism /online /Enable-Feature /FeatureName:TelnetClient\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nYou can send your executable `.bin` or `.elf` file through the Telnet client session to OpenOCD, and instruct OpenOCD to flash it to the chip. You can do something similar with a GDB client.\n\n[[File:Openocd.png|thumb|The procedure to flash firmware to a microcontroller, using OpenOCD.]]\n\n== Debugging with OpenOCD and GDB ==\n\n[UNDER CONSTRUCTION]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n[[Category:Debuggers]]\n[[Category:Free software]]\n\n{{free-software-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{primary sources|date=July 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox software\n| name = OpenOCD\n| logo = <!-- Image name is enough. -->\n| logo alt = \n| logo caption = \n| screenshot = <!-- Image name is enough. -->\n| screenshot size =\n| screenshot alt = \n| caption = \n| collapsible = <!-- Any text here will collapse the screenshot. -->\n| author = Dominic Rath<ref>{{cite web |title=About OpenOCD |url=http://openocd.org/about/ |website=openocd.org |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n| developer = Paul Fertser, \u00d8yvind Harboe, Spencer Oliver\n| released = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| discontinued = no\n| ver layout = <!-- simple (default) or stacked -->\n| latest release version = 0.10.0\n| latest release date = {{Start date and age|2017|01|22|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite web |title=OpenOCD 0.10.0 release is out |url=http://openocd.org/2017/01/openocd-0-10-0-release-is-out/ |website=Open On-Chip Debugger |accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n| latest preview version = \n| latest preview date = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| repo = https://sourceforge.net/p/openocd/code/\n| programming language = [[C (programming language)|C]]\n| operating system = [[Unix-like]], [[Microsoft Windows]]<ref>{{cite web |title=GNU MCU Eclipse OpenOCD |url=https://github.com/gnu-mcu-eclipse/openocd/releases |website=GitHub.com |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n| platform = \n| size = \n| language = \n| language count = <!-- Number only -->\n| language footnote = \n| genre = \n| license = [[GPL#Version_2|GPLv2]]\n| alexa = \n| website = http://openocd.org\n| standard = \n| AsOf = \n}}\n\n'''OpenOCD''' is a [[free software]] [[In-circuit_emulation#On-chip_debugging|on-chip debugging]], [[in-system programming]] and [[Boundary scan|boundary-scan]] testing tool for various [[ARM architecture|ARM]], [[MIPS architecture|MIPS]] and [[RISC-V]] [[microcontroller|microcontrollers]].<ref>{{cite web |title=OpenOCD User\u2019s Guide |url=http://openocd.org/doc/pdf/openocd.pdf |website=openocd.org |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Why your hardware needs an open source debugger |url=https://opensource.com/life/15/5/open-source-on-chip-debugger |website=opensource.com |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n== What is OpenOCD used for? ==\nWriting firmware code (usually a binary or hex-file) to a microcontroller is called '''\"flashing\"'''. To flash, one needs to perform a series of actions involving several hardware and software tools to be successful. OpenOCD is a very popular software tool that plays an important role in this \"flashing procedure\". Aside from flashing, OpenOCD can also be used to '''\"debug\"''' the firmware. For that purpose engineers typically connect a [[GNU Debugger|GDB client]] to OpenOCD.\n\nA good way to understand OpenOCD's role in flashing and debugging firmware on microcontrollers, is to investigate the \"flashing procedure\" in more detail.\n\n=== The flashing procedure ===\nAbsolutely nothing happens when you switch on a new empty microcontroller, because there is simply no code in its Flash memory. The USB port, serial port, ethernet link - or whatever connectivity your chip supports - won't do anything. However, there is one exception: the JTAG (and/or SWD) link to your microcontroller is always intact. This protocol is burned in the silicon. So even an 'empty' microcontroller receives and processes JTAG (and/or SWD) commands. That's why you typically use JTAG (or SWD) to flash the firmware.\n\nIn theory, you can put a [[bootloader]] in your firmware. This way you only need to flash the firmware once with JTAG (or SWD), and you can flash new firmware using the bootloader. However, it is customary to just use JTAG (or SWD) to flash repeatedly during firmware development.\n\nTo actually send the JTAG (or SWD) commands to a microcontroller, you need a '''\"flash/debug probe\"'''. This probe can be a separate device that you connect to the JTAG (or SWD) pins on the microcontroller through a connector. However, some circuit boards have an on-board flash/debug probe right next to the microcontroller. The connection to the JTAG (or SWD) pins is therefore hard-wired on the circuit board.\n\nThe flash/debug probe usually has a USB connector to connect to your computer. Before using it, you'll need to install the USB driver first, which you should download from the website of the probe manufacturer.\n\nOnce the probe is properly installed on your computer and connected to the correct pins on the microcontrollers, you can start OpenOCD. Assuming you've got OpenOCD installed, you can start it this way from your console:\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\" line='line'>\n    $openocd -f openocd_probe.cfg -f openocd_chip.cfg -s <OCDSCRIPTS_LOC> -c \"init; reset halt\"\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nThe files \"openocd_probe.cfg\" and \"openocd_chip.cfg\" are configuration files that describe your probe and microcontroller respectively. You should find these files for your specific microcontroller and probe in the \"scripts\" folder within your OpenOCD installation. Pass these files with the `-f` flag to OpenOCD at startup. Also pass the location to the OpenOCD \"scripts\" folder with the `-s` flag. Finally, you can pass some commands with the `-c` flag that OpenOCD should immediately execute when started.\n\nOpenOCD has no graphical user interface. When it's started, you should see some output in the console telling you if the connection to the microcontroller was successful or not. If successful, OpenOCD starts a \"GDB server\" on TCP port 3333 and a \"Telnet server\" on TCP port 4444 in the background.\n\nOpen a second console and start a Telnet client:\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\" line='line'>\n    $telnet 127.0.0.1 4444\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nIn Windows you might need to enable Telnet first:\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\" line='line'>\n    > dism /online /Enable-Feature /FeatureName:TelnetClient\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nYou can send your executable `.bin` or `.elf` file through the Telnet client session to OpenOCD, and instruct OpenOCD to flash it to the chip. You can do something similar with a GDB client.\n\n[[File:Openocd.png|thumb|The procedure to flash firmware to a microcontroller, using OpenOCD.]]\n\n\n== Debugging with OpenOCD and GDB ==\n\n[UNDER CONSTRUCTION]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n[[Category:Debuggers]]\n[[Category:Free software]]\n\n{{free-software-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Kmulier", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix markup issues.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OpenOCD"}
{"title_page": "Girl Happy", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Girl Happy\n| image          = GirlHappyElvisP.JPG\n| border         = yes\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Boris Sagal]]\n| producer       = [[Joe Pasternak]]\n| writer         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Harvey Bullock (writer)|Harvey Bullock]]\n* [[R.S. Allen]]\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Elvis Presley]]\n* [[Shelley Fabares]]\n}}\n| music          = [[George E. Stoll]]\n| cinematography = [[Philip H. Lathrop]]\n| editing        = Rita Roland\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* Euterpe\n* [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]\n}}\n| distributor    = Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer\n| released       = {{Film date|1965|03|12|Alabama|ref1=<ref name=\"afi\">{{cite web |url=http://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/18794#3 |title=Girl Happy - Details |website=[[AFI Catalog of Feature Films]] |accessdate=July 25, 2018 }}</ref>|1965|04|14|USA}}\n| runtime        = 96 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = $3,250,000 {{small|(US/ Canada rentals)}}<ref>This figure consists of anticipated rentals accruing distributors in North America. See \"Big Rental Pictures of 1965\", ''Variety'', 5 January 1966 p 6 and Tom Lisanti, ''Hollywood Surf and Beach Movies: The First Wave, 1959-1969'', McFarland 2005, p193</ref>\n}}\n'''''Girl Happy''''' is a 1965 American [[musical film|musical]] [[romantic comedy]] and [[beach party film]] starring [[Elvis Presley]] in his eighteenth feature. The movie won a fourth place prize [[Laurel Award]] in the category Top Musical of 1965. It  featured the song \"[[Puppet on a String (Elvis Presley song)|Puppet on a String]]\", which reached #14 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Hot 100, #3 on the Adult Contemporary chart and in Canada, and was certified Gold by the [[RIAA]].\n\n==Plot==\n[[Nightclub singer]] Rusty Wells (Presley) and his band have just closed their engagement at the club where they work in [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]], and are just about ready to leave for their annual spring break trip to [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]]\u2014that is, until the club's owner, Big Frank ([[Harold Stone]]), extends their stay at his club, foiling the band's plans for some sun and fun in Florida.\n\nAt the same time, Big Frank's daughter, college student Valerie ([[Shelley Fabares]]) also takes her spring break in Lauderdale with her friends, which worries her father to no end. So at the suggestion of Rusty (who sees this situation as an opportunity for him and the guys to make Lauderdale after all), Big Frank hires Rusty and his band to make the trip to Lauderdale to look after Valerie to make sure she stays out of trouble. But the task isn't easy, as Rusty and the guys struggle to keep sex-crazed Italian [[exchange student]] Romano (Fabrizio Mioni) away from Valerie, while at the same time Rusty has to keep explaining the situation to his date, a good-time girl named Deena ([[Mary Ann Mobley]]), who has no patience for guys who stand her up or keep her waiting.\n\nRusty's watch over Valerie eventually leads to the two of them falling in love (after Rusty walks Valerie to her motel room, serenading her with \"[[Girl Happy (album)|Puppet on a String]]\").  However, after Big Frank reveals to Valerie that he is paying Rusty to be her chaperone, Valerie becomes angry and devastated to the point of going to a local nightclub, getting drunk, and starting a riot, landing everyone there in jail.\n\nWhen Big Frank arrives in Lauderdale to spring Valerie from jail, he is angry with Rusty at first. But after he sees that Valerie has fallen in love with Rusty, Big Frank makes amends with Rusty, allowing Rusty and Valerie to once again rekindle their relationship.\n\n==Primary cast==\n* [[Elvis Presley]] as Rusty Wells\n* [[Shelley Fabares]] as Valerie Frank\n* [[Harold Stone]] as  Big Frank\n* [[Gary Crosby (actor)|Gary Crosby]] as Andy\n* [[Joby Baker]] as  Wilbur\n* [[Jimmy Hawkins]] as  Doc\n* [[Nita Talbot]] as Sunny Daze\n* [[Mary Ann Mobley]] as Deena Shepherd\n* [[Fabrizio Mioni]] as Romano Orlada\n* Peter Brooks as Brentwood Von Durgenfeld\n* [[Jackie Coogan]] as Sgt. Benson\n* [[John Fiedler]] as Mr. Penchill\n* [[Chris Noel]] as Betsy\n* [[Beverly Adams]] as Girl #2 (uncredited)\n* [[Dan Haggerty]] as Charlie (uncredited)\n* [[Red West]] as Extra in the Kit Kat Club (uncredited)\n\n==Production notes==\nAlthough MGM presented ''Girl Happy'' as a [[beach party film]] (''\"Elvis brings his beat to the beach!\" \"Elvis jumps with the campus crowd to make the beach 'ball' bounce!\"'') and while Presley had previously appeared shirtless in films prior to this, he never appears without a shirt at any time throughout his many scenes at the pool and on the beach in Florida, wearing long sleeves for most of the film - even while water-skiing\n\nFilming began on June 22, 1964 and finished in late July.<ref name=\"afi\" /> Even though the film is set in Fort Lauderdale, Presley did not film any scenes in the city. Primary shooting was done at the MGM studios, while the beach scenes were filmed in southern California. Only second unit filming was done in Fort Lauderdale. \n\nAlternate titles considered were ''The Only Way to Love'' and ''Girl Crazy''. Joe Pasternak had produced the similar spring break movie ''[[Where the Boys Are]]'', which was also set in Fort Lauderdale, Florida, in 1960.\n\n[[Shelley Fabares]], [[Mary Ann Mobley]], and [[Chris Noel]] had each appeared in a [[beach party film]] movie prior to ''Girl Happy'': Fabares in ''[[Ride the Wild Surf]]'', and both Mobley and Noel in ''[[Get Yourself a College Girl]]''. Shelley Fabares sings \"Spring Fever\" in a duet with Elvis, and Nita Talbot sings the song \"Read All About It\". This would the first of three movies in which Fabares would co-star with Elvis. [[Dan Haggerty]], who plays Charlie, would later appear in ''[[The Life and Times of Grizzly Adams]]'' movie and TV series.\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{main|Girl Happy (soundtrack)}}\n\n==Reception==\n[[Howard Thompson (film critic)|Howard Thompson]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' felt that the film \"meanders familiarly,\" and that \"the steady stream of tunes, as rhythmical as they are unoriginal\" were its \"saving grace.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last=Thompson |first=Howard |date=May 27, 1965 |title='Girl Happy' at Forum Has Elvis Presley Singing Again |journal=[[The New York Times]] |page=28 }}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called it \"another musical winner,\" adding, \"A story line unburdened by anything but lightness and a dozen song numbers belted out in singer's customary style provide the type of pleasant fare which Presley's fans have come to expect.\"<ref>{{cite journal |date=January 27, 1965 |title=Girl Happy |journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |page=6 }}</ref> Margaret Harford of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called the film \"another 'beach musical' that looks livelier and fresher than most.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last=Harford |first=Margaret |date=April 16, 1965 |title='Girl Happy' Promises More Box Office Joy for Elvis |journal=[[Los Angeles Times]] |page=Part IV p10 }}</ref> ''[[The Monthly Film Bulletin]]'' called it \"very much a standard Presley vehicle. In other words, Elvis is the only really interesting thing about it.\"<ref>{{cite journal |date=April 1965 |title=Girl Happy |journal=[[The Monthly Film Bulletin]] |volume=32 |issue=375 |page=56 }}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\nThe film made its home video debut in 1988, being released on VHS. When it was reissued on VHS in 1997, the song \"Startin' Tonight\" was deleted. It was eventually reinstated back into the film when it made its DVD debut in 2007.\n\n===DVD reviews===\n*[http://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/read.php?ID=30398 Elvis - The Hollywood Collection (Kissin' Cousins/Girl Happy/Tickle Me/Stay Away, Joe/Live a Little, Love a Little/Charro!)] Review by Stuart Galbraith IV at [http://www.dvdtalk.com/ DVD Talk], September 11, 2007.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070819033211/http://thedvdlounge.insidepulse.com/articles/69433/2007/08/07/igirl-happyi--dvd-review.html Review] by Mike Noyes at [https://web.archive.org/web/20070827074252/http://thedvdlounge.insidepulse.com/topics/reviews The DVD Lounge], 08.07.2007.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of American films of 1965]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.elvispresley.com.au/ For Elvis Fans Only] Website decitated to Elvis Presley's Movies.\n* {{IMDb title|0059224}}\n* {{amg title|19803}}\n* {{tcmdb title|id=2117}}\n\n{{Elvis Presley}}\n{{Boris Sagal}}\n\n[[Category:Films directed by Boris Sagal]]\n[[Category:1965 films]]\n[[Category:1960s musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:1960s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Florida]]\n[[Category:Films set in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Films shot in California]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Florida]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Joe Pasternak]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Girl Happy\n| image          = GirlHappyElvisP.JPG\n| border         = yes\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Boris Sagal]]\n| producer       = [[Joe Pasternak]]\n| writer         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Harvey Bullock (writer)|Harvey Bullock]]\n* [[R.S. Allen]]\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Elvis Presley]]\n* [[Shelley Fabares]]\n}}\n| music          = [[George E. Stoll]]\n| cinematography = [[Philip H. Lathrop]]\n| editing        = Rita Roland\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* Euterpe\n* [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]\n}}\n| distributor    = Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer\n| released       = {{Film date|1965|03|12|Alabama|ref1=<