ays out of trouble. But the task isn't easy, as Rusty and the guys struggle to keep sex-crazed Italian [[exchange student]] Romano (Fabrizio Mioni) away from Valerie, while at the same time Rusty has to keep explaining the situation to his date, a good-time girl named Deena ([[Mary Ann Mobley]]), who has no patience for guys who stand her up or keep her waiting.\n\nRusty's watch over Valerie eventually leads to the two of them falling in love (after Rusty walks Valerie to her motel room, serenading her with \"[[Girl Happy (album)|Puppet on a String]]\").  However, after Big Frank reveals to Valerie that he is paying Rusty to be her chaperone, Valerie becomes angry and devastated to the point of going to a local nightclub, getting drunk, and starting a riot, landing everyone there in jail.\n\nWhen Big Frank arrives in Lauderdale to spring Valerie from jail, he is angry with Rusty at first. But after he sees that Valerie has fallen in love with Rusty, Big Frank makes amends with Rusty, allowing Rusty and Valerie to once again rekindle their relationship.\n\n==Primary cast==\n* [[Elvis Presley]] as Rusty Wells\n* [[Shelley Fabares]] as Valerie Frank\n* [[Harold Stone]] as  Big Frank\n* [[Gary Crosby (actor)|Gary Crosby]] as Andy\n* [[Joby Baker]] as  Wilbur\n* Jimmy Hawkins as  Doc\n* [[Nita Talbot]] as Sunny Daze\n* [[Mary Ann Mobley]] as Deena Shepherd\n* [[Fabrizio Mioni]] as Romano Orlada\n* Peter Brooks as Brentwood Von Durgenfeld\n* [[Jackie Coogan]] as Sgt. Benson\n* [[John Fiedler]] as Mr. Penchill\n* [[Chris Noel]] as Betsy\n* [[Beverly Adams]] as Girl #2 (uncredited)\n* [[Dan Haggerty]] as Charlie (uncredited)\n* [[Red West]] as Extra in the Kit Kat Club (uncredited)\n\n==Production notes==\nAlthough MGM presented ''Girl Happy'' as a [[beach party film]] (''\"Elvis brings his beat to the beach!\" \"Elvis jumps with the campus crowd to make the beach 'ball' bounce!\"'') and while Presley had previously appeared shirtless in films prior to this, he never appears without a shirt at any time throughout his many scenes at the pool and on the beach in Florida, wearing long sleeves for most of the film - even while water-skiing\n\nFilming began on June 22, 1964 and finished in late July.<ref name=\"afi\" /> Even though the film is set in Fort Lauderdale, Presley did not film any scenes in the city. Primary shooting was done at the MGM studios, while the beach scenes were filmed in southern California. Only second unit filming was done in Fort Lauderdale. \n\nAlternate titles considered were ''The Only Way to Love'' and ''Girl Crazy''. Joe Pasternak had produced the similar spring break movie ''[[Where the Boys Are]]'', which was also set in Fort Lauderdale, Florida, in 1960.\n\n[[Shelley Fabares]], [[Mary Ann Mobley]], and [[Chris Noel]] had each appeared in a [[beach party film]] movie prior to ''Girl Happy'': Fabares in ''[[Ride the Wild Surf]]'', and both Mobley and Noel in ''[[Get Yourself a College Girl]]''. Shelley Fabares sings \"Spring Fever\" in a duet with Elvis, and Nita Talbot sings the song \"Read All About It\". This would the first of three movies in which Fabares would co-star with Elvis. [[Dan Haggerty]], who plays Charlie, would later appear in ''[[The Life and Times of Grizzly Adams]]'' movie and TV series.\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{main|Girl Happy (soundtrack)}}\n\n==Reception==\n[[Howard Thompson (film critic)|Howard Thompson]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' felt that the film \"meanders familiarly,\" and that \"the steady stream of tunes, as rhythmical as they are unoriginal\" were its \"saving grace.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last=Thompson |first=Howard |date=May 27, 1965 |title='Girl Happy' at Forum Has Elvis Presley Singing Again |journal=[[The New York Times]] |page=28 }}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called it \"another musical winner,\" adding, \"A story line unburdened by anything but lightness and a dozen song numbers belted out in singer's customary style provide the type of pleasant fare which Presley's fans have come to expect.\"<ref>{{cite journal |date=January 27, 1965 |title=Girl Happy |journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |page=6 }}</ref> Margaret Harford of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called the film \"another 'beach musical' that looks livelier and fresher than most.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last=Harford |first=Margaret |date=April 16, 1965 |title='Girl Happy' Promises More Box Office Joy for Elvis |journal=[[Los Angeles Times]] |page=Part IV p10 }}</ref> ''[[The Monthly Film Bulletin]]'' called it \"very much a standard Presley vehicle. In other words, Elvis is the only really interesting thing about it.\"<ref>{{cite journal |date=April 1965 |title=Girl Happy |journal=[[The Monthly Film Bulletin]] |volume=32 |issue=375 |page=56 }}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\nThe film made its home video debut in 1988, being released on VHS. When it was reissued on VHS in 1997, the song \"Startin' Tonight\" was deleted. It was eventually reinstated back into the film when it made its DVD debut in 2007.\n\n===DVD reviews===\n*[http://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/read.php?ID=30398 Elvis - The Hollywood Collection (Kissin' Cousins/Girl Happy/Tickle Me/Stay Away, Joe/Live a Little, Love a Little/Charro!)] Review by Stuart Galbraith IV at [http://www.dvdtalk.com/ DVD Talk], September 11, 2007.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070819033211/http://thedvdlounge.insidepulse.com/articles/69433/2007/08/07/igirl-happyi--dvd-review.html Review] by Mike Noyes at [https://web.archive.org/web/20070827074252/http://thedvdlounge.insidepulse.com/topics/reviews The DVD Lounge], 08.07.2007.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of American films of 1965]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.elvispresley.com.au/ For Elvis Fans Only] Website decitated to Elvis Presley's Movies.\n* {{IMDb title|0059224}}\n* {{amg title|19803}}\n* {{tcmdb title|id=2117}}\n\n{{Elvis Presley}}\n{{Boris Sagal}}\n\n[[Category:Films directed by Boris Sagal]]\n[[Category:1965 films]]\n[[Category:1960s musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:1960s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Florida]]\n[[Category:Films set in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Films shot in California]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Florida]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Joe Pasternak]]\n", "name_user": "MortimerBirdie", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Girl_Happy"}
{"title_page": "Brian Dyson", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name         = Brian Dyson \n|birth_name   = \n|birth_date   =  [[September, 1935]]\n|birth_place  = [[Argentina]]<ref name=TimeOut>{{cite web|last=Shames|first=Laurence|date=20 September 1987|title=Time Out For Tension|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/20/magazine/time-out-for-tension.html?pagewanted=all|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Greenwald|first=John|date=12 April 2005|title=Coca-Cola's Big Fizzle|url=http://content.time.com/time/subscriber/printout/0,8816,1048370,00.html?iid=sr-link1|magazine=Time|accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Brian Dyson compares Argentine crisis to 'a tango'|date=8 May 2002|url=http://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,brian-dyson-compara-crise-argentina-a-um-tango,20020508p29581|work=Estadao|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref>\n|nationality  = [[Argentinian]]\n|alma_mater   = [[Harvard Business School]]\n|education    = [[University of Buenos Aires]]\n|occupation   = Former CEO of [[The Coca-Cola Company]]\n|spouse       = Evelyn Penelope Jane Dyson\n|website      =  \n}}\n\n'''Brian G. Dyson''' (born September, 1935)<ref name=TimeOut/> was the [[chief executive officer]] (CEO) of [[Coca-Cola Enterprises Inc.]] from 1986 to 1991.\n\nBrian is also known for his \u201cfive balls\u201d speech.<ref>{{cite web|date=31 July 2015|title=9 Thought-Provoking Quotes About Work-Life Balance|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/salesforce/2015/07/31/9-thought-provoking-quotes-about-work-life-balance/#539948c4309e|work=Forbes|accessdate=9 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nHe joined Coca-Cola Co. in Venezuela in 1959 and worked for many years in [[South America]], the [[Caribbean]] and Mexico. In 1978 Dyson was named the [[President (corporate title)|President]] of Coca-Cola United States, the Company's U.S. soft drink division. In 1983, he was named president of Coca-Cola North America, with responsibility for the Company's entire [[North America]] portfolio. In 1986 Dyson was named president and [[Chief Executive Officer]] (CEO) of [[Coca-Cola Enterprises]] (CCE).<ref name=BP>{{cite web|last=Gilpin|first=Kenneth|date=15 July 1986|title=BUSINESS PEOPLE; COKE PICKS LEADER FOR NEW UNIT|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/07/15/business/business-people-coke-picks-leader-for-new-unit.html|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe served as a Senior Consultant to The Coca-Cola Company from January 1992 to October 1993. He retired from The Coca-Cola Company in 1994, but remained active as a consultant to the Company. In August 2001 he came out of retirement and accepted the position of [[Vice Chairman]] and [[Chief Operating Officer]] (COO) of The Coca-Cola Company.\n\nDyson was the one who at first changed old Coke's name and then restored it.<ref name=BP/>\n\nHe is a Member of Advisory Board of Linley Capital. Since May 1995, Dyson served as a Director of Audits & Surveys Worldwide Inc. He served as the Chairman of the Board of PlusPharma since August 2004. Brian G. Dyson has been the President of Chatham International Corp. since December 1993.\n\nHe earned his BA from Facultad de Ciencias Econ\u00f3micas in [[University of Buenos Aires]]. He later attended [[Harvard Business School]]. An author of short stories, in 1996 he published a novel, ''Pepper in the Blood''.<ref>{{cite book|title=ExecutiveHealth|p=57\u201361|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-dtEDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA57&lpg=PA57&dq=brian+dyson+coca+cola&source=bl&ots=81eEsoBdsq&sig=AIscEsVXshCd-8gimoLb5u5_TYk&hl=ru&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi_3ayO-d7ZAhVG3CwKHdPcCvM4KBDoAQg6MAM#v=onepage&q=brian%20dyson%20coca%20cola&f=false|accessdate=9 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBrian Dyson is married to Penny Dyson. In 1978, the family moved to [[Atlanta]].<ref name=TimeOut/> Brian and Penny Dyson have two children.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dyson, Brian}}\n[[Category:American chief executives of food industry companies]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American drink industry businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Chief operating officers]]\n[[Category:University of Buenos Aires alumni]]\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n\n\n{{US-CEO-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name         = Brian Dyson \n|birth_name   = \n|birth_date   =  [[September, 1935]]\n|birth_place  = [[Argentina]]<ref name=TimeOut>{{cite web|last=Shames|first=Laurence|date=20 September 1987|title=Time Out For Tension|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/20/magazine/time-out-for-tension.html?pagewanted=all|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Greenwald|first=John|date=12 April 2005|title=Coca-Cola's Big Fizzle|url=http://content.time.com/time/subscriber/printout/0,8816,1048370,00.html?iid=sr-link1|magazine=Time|accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Brian Dyson compares Argentine crisis to 'a tango'|date=8 May 2002|url=http://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,brian-dyson-compara-crise-argentina-a-um-tango,20020508p29581|work=Estadao|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref>\n|residence    = United States\n|nationality  = [[Argentinian]]\n|alma_mater   = [[Harvard Business School]]\n|education    = [[University of Buenos Aires]]\n|occupation   = Former CEO of [[The Coca-Cola Company]]\n|website      =  \n}}\n\n'''Brian G. Dyson''' (born September, 1935)<ref name=TimeOut/> was the [[chief executive officer]] (CEO) of [[Coca-Cola Enterprises Inc.]] from 1986 to 1991.\n\nBrian is also known for his \u201cfive balls\u201d speech.<ref>{{cite web|date=31 July 2015|title=9 Thought-Provoking Quotes About Work-Life Balance|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/salesforce/2015/07/31/9-thought-provoking-quotes-about-work-life-balance/#539948c4309e|work=Forbes|accessdate=9 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nHe joined Coca-Cola Co. in Venezuela in 1959 and worked for many years in [[South America]], the [[Caribbean]] and Mexico. In 1978 Dyson was named the [[President (corporate title)|President]] of Coca-Cola United States, the Company's U.S. soft drink division. In 1983, he was named president of Coca-Cola North America, with responsibility for the Company's entire [[North America]] portfolio. In 1986 Dyson was named president and [[Chief Executive Officer]] (CEO) of [[Coca-Cola Enterprises]] (CCE).<ref name=BP>{{cite web|last=Gilpin|first=Kenneth|date=15 July 1986|title=BUSINESS PEOPLE; COKE PICKS LEADER FOR NEW UNIT|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/07/15/business/business-people-coke-picks-leader-for-new-unit.html|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe served as a Senior Consultant to The Coca-Cola Company from January 1992 to October 1993. He retired from The Coca-Cola Company in 1994, but remained active as a consultant to the Company. In August 2001 he came out of retirement and accepted the position of [[Vice Chairman]] and [[Chief Operating Officer]] (COO) of The Coca-Cola Company.\n\nDyson was the one who at first changed old Coke's name and then restored it.<ref name=BP/>\n\nHe is a Member of Advisory Board of Linley Capital. Since May 1995, Dyson served as a Director of Audits & Surveys Worldwide Inc. He served as the Chairman of the Board of PlusPharma since August 2004. Brian G. Dyson has been the President of Chatham International Corp. since December 1993.\n\nHe earned his BA from Facultad de Ciencias Econ\u00f3micas in [[University of Buenos Aires]]. He later attended [[Harvard Business School]]. An author of short stories, in 1996 he published a novel, ''Pepper in the Blood''.<ref>{{cite book|title=ExecutiveHealth|p=57\u201361|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-dtEDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA57&lpg=PA57&dq=brian+dyson+coca+cola&source=bl&ots=81eEsoBdsq&sig=AIscEsVXshCd-8gimoLb5u5_TYk&hl=ru&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi_3ayO-d7ZAhVG3CwKHdPcCvM4KBDoAQg6MAM#v=onepage&q=brian%20dyson%20coca%20cola&f=false|accessdate=9 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBrian Dyson is married to Penny Dyson. In 1978, the family moved to [[Atlanta]].<ref name=TimeOut/> Brian and Penny Dyson have two children.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dyson, Brian}}\n[[Category:American chief executives of food industry companies]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American drink industry businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Chief operating officers]]\n[[Category:University of Buenos Aires alumni]]\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n\n\n{{US-CEO-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wc721", "label": "safe", "comment": "update spouse", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brian_Dyson"}
{"title_page": "Department of Homeland Security v. Thuraissigiam", "text_new": "{{Infobox SCOTUS case\n  |Litigants=Department of Homeland Security v. Thuraissigiam\n  |ArgueDate=March 2\n  |ArgueYear=2020\n  |DecideDate=\n  |DecideYear=\n  |FullName=Department of Homeland Security, et a., petitioners v. Vijayakumar Thuraissigiam\n  |USVol=\n  |USPage=\n  |ParallelCitations=\n  |Docket=19-161\n  |OralArgument=https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts10/oral_argument_audio/24973\n  |OpinionAnnouncement=\n  |Prior=Motion to dismiss granted, ''Thuraissigiam v. United States Dep't of Homeland Sec.'', 287 [[F. Supp. 3d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infdco20180309c87 1077] (S.D. Cal. 2018); reversed, 917 [[F.3d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20190307136 1097] (9th Cir. 2019); [[Certiorari|cert]]. granted, 140 S. Ct. 427 (2019).\n  |Subsequent=\n  |Holding=\n  |Majority=\n  |JoinMajority=\n  |Concurrence=\n  |JoinConcurrence=\n  |Concurrence2=\n  |JoinConcurrence2=\n  |Concurrence/Dissent=\n  |JoinConcurrence/Dissent=\n  |Dissent=\n  |JoinDissent=\n  |Dissent2=\n  |JoinDissent2=\n  |LawsApplied=[[Article One of the United States Constitution|U.S. Const. art. I]]<br />[[Illegal Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act of 1996]]\n}}\n'''''Department of Homeland Security v. Thuraissigiam''''' is a case of refugee removal whose appeal is currently pending before the [[Supreme Court of the United States]].<ref name=nytimes2020-01-20/><ref name=AcluThuraissigiam/>\n\n== Background ==\n\n=== Prior case law ===\n\nThe [[Suspension Clause]] of [[Article One of the United States Constitution]] states that the writ of ''[[habeas corpus]]'' shall not be suspended except when a suspension may be required in cases of invasion or rebellion. In 1996 the [[Department of Homeland Security]] made an internal determination that detained individuals they deemed were subject to \"[[expedited removal]]\" were not entitled to access to the usual court remedies, including a [[writ of habeas corpus]].<ref name=\"nytimes2020-01-20\" /> According to [[Linda Greenhouse]], writing in ''[[The New York Times]]'', expedited removal is intended for immigrants (or ''\"aliens\"'' in American terms) ''\"who are deemed inadmissable upon arrival\"''.<ref name=nytimes2020-01-20/> Immigrants are entitled to claim they are entitled to refugee status, if they say they have a ''\u201ccredible fear of persecution or torture\u201d'', if returned home.\n\nA single immigration officer will then make a determination as to whether the fear is credible.<ref name=nytimes2020-01-20/>  If he or she determines it is credible, a panel will hold a hearing to explore the immigrant's refugee claim, in detail.  However, under the [[Illegal Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act of 1996|Illegal Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act]],<ref>[[Illegal Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act of 1996]], {{USStatute|104|208|110|3009-546}}, Div. C.</ref> if the single frontline officer's initial assessment is that the fear is not credible, there is no route of appeal.\n\n=== Facts of the case ===\n\nThe respondent, Vijayakumar Thuraissiam, is an \"inadmissible alien who was apprehended almost immediately after illegally crossing the U.S. border and was placed into expedited removal proceedings\".<ref name=\"qp\">{{cite web |title=19-161 Dept. of Homeland Security v. Thuraissigiam: Question Presented |url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/qp/19-00161qp.pdf |website=U.S. Supreme Court |accessdate=April 24, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191213214307/https://www.supremecourt.gov/qp/19-00161qp.pdf |archivedate=December 13, 2019 |date=October 18, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> According to the [[American Civil Liberties Union]], which is representing Thuraissiam in the Supreme Court, Thuraissiam is a former [[Tamil people|Tamilian]] resident of [[Sri Lanka]], who fled from Sri Lanka in order to \"escape torture, beatings, and likely death\".<ref name=\"aclu\">{{cite web |title=Department of Homeland Security v. Thuraissigiam |url=https://www.aclu.org/cases/department-homeland-security-v-vijayakumar-thuraissigiam |website=American Civil Liberties Union |accessdate=April 24, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224111139/https://www.aclu.org/cases/department-homeland-security-v-vijayakumar-thuraissigiam |archivedate=February 24, 2020 |date=January 17, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> An asylum officer interviewed Thuraissiam and concluded that he lacked a \"credible fear of persecution on a protected ground or a credible fear of torture\".<ref name=\"qp\" />\n\n=== Lower court proceedings ===\n\nAfter reviewing Thuraissiam's case, an immigration judge agreed with the immigration officer's conclusions, and ordinarily, this would have been a final decision not subject to appeal.<ref name=\"qp\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Department of Homeland Security v. Thuraissigiam: Joint Appendix - Order of the Immigration Judge |url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/DocketPDF/19/19-161/125001/20191209192603650_19-161%20Thuraissigiam%20J.A..pdf |website=U.S. Supreme Court |accessdate=April 24, 2020 |page=97}}</ref> Nevertheless, Thuraissiam filed a petition for a writ of ''habeas corpus'' in the [[U.S. District Court for the Southern District of California]], which dismissed the petition for lack of [[jurisdiction]] under the Illegal Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act, specifically the section codified as 8 [[United States Code|U.S.C.]] section 1252(e)(2). Thuraissiam then appealed to the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]], which reversed, holding that section 1252(e)(2) was [[unconstitutional]] because it violated the Suspension Clause.<ref name=\"qp\" />\n\n== Supreme Court ==\nThe Department of Homeland Security filed a petition for a [[certiorari|writ of ''certiorari'']] in the Supreme Court of the United States, which granted ''certiorari'' on October 18, 2019, in order to review \"whether, as applied to respondent, Section 1252(e)(2) is unconstitutional under the Suspension Clause\".<ref name=\"qp\" /> Oral arguments were held on March 2, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=Department of Homeland Security v. Thuraissigiam: Oral Argument - Audio |url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/oral_arguments/audio/2019/19-161 |website=U.S. Supreme Court |accessdate=April 24, 2020 |date=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<!-- \n| archivedate = | url-status = live| archiveurl = \n| url-status = live| archivedate = | archiveurl = \n| url-status = dead| archivedate = | archiveurl = \n -->\n{{Reflist|refs= \n<ref name=AcluThuraissigiam>{{cite court |litigants=Thuraissigiam v. United States Dep't of Homeland Sec. |vol=917 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=1097 |pinpoint= |court=9th Cir. |date=2019 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20190307136 |accessdate=2020-01-11 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n<!-- {{cite news     \n| url         = \n| title       = \n| work        = \n| author      = \n| date        = \n| page        = \n| location    = \n| isbn        = \n| language    = \n| trans-title = \n| archiveurl  = \n| archivedate = \n| accessdate  = 2020-01-02\n| url-status  = live\n| quote       = \n}}\n</ref>\n\n{{cite news     \n| url         = \n| title       = \n| work        = \n| author      = \n| date        = \n| page        = \n| location    = \n| isbn        = \n| language    = \n| trans-title = \n| archiveurl  = \n| archivedate = \n| accessdate  = 2020-01-02\n| url-status  = live\n| quote       = \n}}\n</ref>\n -->\n<ref name=nytimes2020-01-20>\n{{cite news     \n| url         = https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/02/opinion/guantanamo-detention-supreme-court.html\n| title       = An Old Battle Resumes at the Supreme Court\n| work        = [[The New York Times]]\n| author      = [[Linda Greenhouse]]\n| date        = 2020-01-20\n| page        = \n| location    = \n| isbn        = \n| language    = \n| trans-title = \n| archiveurl  = \n| archivedate = \n| accessdate  = 2020-01-02\n| url-status  = live\n| quote       = The question in Department of Homeland Security v. Thuraissigiam is whether a 1996 federal immigration law unconstitutionally stripped the federal courts of jurisdiction over cases, including habeas corpus cases, brought by undocumented immigrants who are subject to what the law designated as {{'}}expedited removal.{{'}}\n}}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n[[Category:United States Supreme Court cases]]\n[[Category:Refugees]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox SCOTUS case\n  |Litigants=Department of Homeland Security v. Thuraissigiam\n  |ArgueDate=March 2\n  |ArgueYear=2020\n  |DecideDate=\n  |DecideYear=\n  |FullName=Department of Homeland Security, et a., petitioners v. Vijayakumar Thuraissigiam\n  |USVol=\n  |USPage=\n  |ParallelCitations=\n  |Docket=19-161\n  |OralArgument=https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts10/oral_argument_audio/24973\n  |OpinionAnnouncement=\n  |Prior=Motion to dismiss granted, ''Thuraissigiam v. United States Dep't of Homeland Sec.'', 287 [[F. Supp. 3d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infdco20180309c87 1077] (S.D. Cal. 2018); reversed, 917 [[F.3d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20190307136 1097] (9th Cir. 2019); [[Certiorari|cert]]. granted, 140 S. Ct. 427 (2019).\n  |Subsequent=\n  |Holding=\n  |Majority=\n  |JoinMajority=\n  |Concurrence=\n  |JoinConcurrence=\n  |Concurrence2=\n  |JoinConcurrence2=\n  |Concurrence/Dissent=\n  |JoinConcurrence/Dissent=\n  |Dissent=\n  |JoinDissent=\n  |Dissent2=\n  |JoinDissent2=\n  |LawsApplied=[[Article One of the United States Constitution|U.S. Const. art. I]]<br />[[Illegal Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act of 1996]]\n}}\n'''''Department of Homeland Security v. Thuraissigiam''''' is a case of refugee removal whose appeal is currently pending before the [[Supreme Court of the United States]].<ref name=nytimes2020-01-20/><ref name=AcluThuraissigiam/>\n\n== Background ==\n\n=== Prior case law ===\n\nThe [[Suspension Clause]] of [[Article One of the United States Constitution]] states that the writ of ''[[habeas corpus]]'' shall not be suspended except when a suspension may be required in cases of invasion or rebellion. In 1996 the [[Department of Homeland Security]] made an internal determination that detained individuals they deemed were subject to \"[[expedited removal]]\" were not entitled to access to the usual court remedies, including a [[writ of habeas corpus]].<ref name=\"nytimes2020-01-20\" /> According to [[Linda Greenhouse]], writing in ''[[The New York Times]]'', expedited removal is intended for immigrants (or ''\"aliens\"'' in American terms) ''\"who are deemed inadmissable upon arrival\"''.<ref name=nytimes2020-01-20/> Immigrants are entitled to claim they are entitled to refugee status, if they say they have a ''\u201ccredible fear of persecution or torture\u201d'', if returned home.\n\nA single immigration officer will then make a determination as to whether the fear is credible.<ref name=nytimes2020-01-20/>  If he or she determines it is credible, a panel will hold a hearing to explore the immigrant's refugee claim, in detail.  However, under the [[Illegal Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act of 1996|Illegal Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act]],<ref>[[Illegal Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act of 1996]], {{USStatute|104|208|110|3009-546}}, Div. C.</ref> if the single frontline officer's initial assessment is that the fear is not credible, there is no route of appeal.\n\n=== Facts of the case ===\n\nThe respondent, Vijayakumar Thuraissiam, is an \"inadmissible alien who was apprehended almost immediately after illegally crossing the U.S. border and was placed into expedited removal proceedings\".<ref name=\"qp\">{{cite web |title=19-161 Dept. of Homeland Security v. Thuraissigiam: Question Presented |url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/qp/19-00161qp.pdf |website=U.S. Supreme Court |accessdate=April 24, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191213214307/https://www.supremecourt.gov/qp/19-00161qp.pdf |archivedate=December 13, 2019 |date=October 18, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> According to the [[American Civil Liberties Union]], which is representing Thuraissiam in the Supreme Court, Thuraissiam is a former [[Tamil people|Tamilian]] resident of [[Sri Lanka]], who fled from Sri Lanka in order to \"escape torture, beatings, and likely death\".<ref name=\"aclu\">{{cite web |title=Department of Homeland Security v. Thuraissigiam |url=https://www.aclu.org/cases/department-homeland-security-v-vijayakumar-thuraissigiam |website=American Civil Liberties Union |accessdate=April 24, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224111139/https://www.aclu.org/cases/department-homeland-security-v-vijayakumar-thuraissigiam |archivedate=February 24, 2020 |date=January 17, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> An asylum officer interviewed Thuraissiam and concluded that he lacked a \"credible fear of persecution on a protected ground or a credible fear of torture\".<ref name=\"qp\" />\n\n=== Lower court proceedings ===\n\nAfter reviewing Thuraissiam's case, an immigration judge agreed with the immigration officer's conclusions, and ordinarily, this would have been a final decision not subject to appeal.<ref name=\"qp\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Department of Homeland Security v. Thuraissigiam: Joint Appendix - Order of the Immigration Judge |url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/DocketPDF/19/19-161/125001/20191209192603650_19-161%20Thuraissigiam%20J.A..pdf |website=U.S. Supreme Court |accessdate=April 24, 2020 |page=97}}</ref> Nevertheless, Thuraissiam filed a petition for a writ of ''habeas corpus'' in the [[U.S. District Court for the Southern District of California]], which dismissed the petition for lack of [[jurisdiction]] under the Illegal Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act, specifically the section codified as 8 [[United States Code|U.S.C.]] section 1252(e)(2). Thuraissiam then appealed to the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]], which reversed, holding that section 1252(e)(2) was [[unconstitutional]] because it violated the Suspension Clause.<ref name=\"qp\" />\n\n== Supreme Court ==\nThe Department of Homeland Security filed a petition for a [[certiorari|writ of''certiorari'']] in the Supreme Court of the United States, which granted ''certiorari'' on October 18, 2019, in order to review \"whether, as applied to respondent, Section 1252(e)(2) is unconstitutional under the Suspension Clause\".<ref name=\"qp\" /> Oral arguments were held on March 2, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=Department of Homeland Security v. Thuraissigiam: Oral Argument - Audio |url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/oral_arguments/audio/2019/19-161 |website=U.S. Supreme Court |accessdate=April 24, 2020 |date=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<!-- \n| archivedate = | url-status = live| archiveurl = \n| url-status = live| archivedate = | archiveurl = \n| url-status = dead| archivedate = | archiveurl = \n -->\n{{Reflist|refs= \n<ref name=AcluThuraissigiam>{{cite court |litigants=Thuraissigiam v. United States Dep't of Homeland Sec. |vol=917 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=1097 |pinpoint= |court=9th Cir. |date=2019 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20190307136 |accessdate=2020-01-11 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n<!-- {{cite news     \n| url         = \n| title       = \n| work        = \n| author      = \n| date        = \n| page        = \n| location    = \n| isbn        = \n| language    = \n| trans-title = \n| archiveurl  = \n| archivedate = \n| accessdate  = 2020-01-02\n| url-status  = live\n| quote       = \n}}\n</ref>\n\n{{cite news     \n| url         = \n| title       = \n| work        = \n| author      = \n| date        = \n| page        = \n| location    = \n| isbn        = \n| language    = \n| trans-title = \n| archiveurl  = \n| archivedate = \n| accessdate  = 2020-01-02\n| url-status  = live\n| quote       = \n}}\n</ref>\n -->\n<ref name=nytimes2020-01-20>\n{{cite news     \n| url     